    info ="<html><body><p>Attapulgite is a magnesium aluminium phyllosilicate clay used as an adsorbent for the symptomatic treatment of diarrhea. It has been used in over-the-counter anti-diarrheal products. Its medical use has declined with modern treatments, but it is still available in some regions.</p><h4>Pharmacokinetics</h4><p>No human pharmacokinetic data available as attapulgite is a non-absorbed, non-systemic gastrointestinal adsorbent. Not absorbed into systemic circulation; parameters estimated as null/zero.</p><h4>References</h4><ol><li><p>Willhite, CC, et al., &amp; McLellan, CJ (2012). Total allowable concentrations of monomeric inorganic aluminum and hydrated aluminum silicates in drinking water. <i>Critical reviews in toxicology</i> 42(5) 358–442. DOI:<a href=&quot;https://doi.org/10.3109/10408444.2012.674101&quot;>10.3109/10408444.2012.674101</a>  PUBMED:<a href=&quot;https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22512666/&quot;>https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22512666</a></p></li><li><p>Arif, A, et al., &amp; Khan, WS (2024). Lipase-copper complex/chitosan microspheres; loaded with attapulgite used for the treatment of E. coli-induced diarrhea. <i>International journal of biological macromolecules</i> 277(Pt 4) 134167–None. DOI:<a href=&quot;https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijbiomac.2024.134167&quot;>10.1016/j.ijbiomac.2024.134167</a>  PUBMED:<a href=&quot;https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39067724/&quot;>https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39067724</a></p></li></ol></body></html>",
